<div>
SO successful is <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a>'s <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> that is has become a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Blueprint" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Blueprint" target="_blank">blueprint</a> for how a modernday <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_arts" target="_blank">arts</a> facility should be run with many <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City" target="_blank">cities</a> around the world keen to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Richie_Havens" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Richie_Havens" target="_blank">follow</a> its setupThat's quite a turnaround when you consider the venue was so disliked when it reopened in 1996 as the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> that <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> turned their back on itLess than 10 years ago when <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Francis_of_Assisi" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Francis_of_Assisi" target="_blank">Francis</a> McKee took over as <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Board_of_directors" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Board_of_directors" target="_blank">director</a> he started a quiet revolution with a shift to a more <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Democracy" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Democracy" target="_blank">democratic</a> way of working and a return in many ways to the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethos" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ethos" target="_blank">ethos</a> of the old Third Eye CentreThe simple act of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Opening_credits" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Opening_credits" target="_blank">opening</a> the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Doors" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Doors" target="_blank">doors</a> welcoming <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" target="_blank">artists</a> and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Performing_arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Performing_arts" target="_blank">performers</a> as well as the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public" target="_blank">public</a> in and encouraging them to stay has proved to be the perfect <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Business" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Business" target="_blank">business</a> modelFrancis's thinking was inspired by the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Redevelopment" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Redevelopment" target="_blank">redevelopment</a> of the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" target="_blank">building</a> between 1999 and 2001 that saw it take over a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Villa" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Villa" target="_blank">villa</a> at the back and a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" target="_blank">building</a> on <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Robert_Falcon_Scott" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Robert_Falcon_Scott" target="_blank">Scott</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Street" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Street" target="_blank">Street</a> The <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Work_of_art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Work_of_art" target="_blank">work</a> doubled the size of the centre but with the operational budget not changing some lateral thinking was required&quotTo just have <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> in that <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" target="_blank">building</a> was going to be reasonably arrogant and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lonely_Planet" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lonely_Planet" target="_blank">lonely</a> It didn't seem sensible in terms of public money and it did seem there was a huge amount of beautiful <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Space" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Space" target="_blank">space</a>&quot he explains&quotSo in a way by 2006 when I started I was told I could do what I <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Wanted" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Wanted" target="_blank">wanted</a> That was the big blessing because once I was told that for instance the office space was <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Film_editing" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Film_editing" target="_blank">cut</a> in half and also used as a residency <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Space" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Space" target="_blank">space</a>&quotBig <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Office" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Office" target="_blank">offices</a> for a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Board_of_directors" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Board_of_directors" target="_blank">director</a> and a PA seemed irrelevant a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" target="_blank">lot</a> of the spaces were repurposed to get more <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" target="_blank">art</a> in We thought if you can see <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" target="_blank">art</a> more <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> have the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Space" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Space" target="_blank">space</a> to do <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" target="_blank">art</a>&quotThen we realised <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> who <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Wanted" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Wanted" target="_blank">wanted</a> to use the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" target="_blank">building</a> couldn't afford to so it was better to give it away and let them use this beautiful <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" target="_blank">building</a> and it brings in an <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Audience" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Audience" target="_blank">audience</a>&quotIf we can make the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Building" target="_blank">building</a> useful we justify our existence The momentum has <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Built_environment" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Built_environment" target="_blank">built</a> up over the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Millennium" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Millennium" target="_blank">years</a> you can see now how it all <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Work_of_art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Work_of_art" target="_blank">works</a>&quotIt recently won the prize for Best <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Culture" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Culture" target="_blank">Cultural</a> Venue at the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow" target="_blank">Glasgow</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Award" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Award" target="_blank">Awards</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Capitol_Records" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Capitol_Records" target="_blank">recognition</a> that the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> is as much loved by artsgoers as makersThe attendance figures say it all In 201415 more than 42000 <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> attended 802 eventsWith 43 staff including fulltime parttime and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Freelancer" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Freelancer" target="_blank">freelance</a> across administration <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Computer_programming" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Computer_programming" target="_blank">programming</a> curatorial <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/2006" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/2006" target="_blank">events</a> development communications <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Technical_drawing" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Technical_drawing" target="_blank">technical</a> install front of house and cleaning the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> is an example in these recessionary <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Times" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Times" target="_blank">times</a> of a success storyNow funded by Creative Scotland as a hub it runs a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Core" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Core" target="_blank">core</a> programme of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Exhibition" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Exhibition" target="_blank">exhibitions</a> and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/2006" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/2006" target="_blank">events</a> as well as hosting the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Work_of_art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Work_of_art" target="_blank">work</a> of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" target="_blank">artists</a> from at home and abroad&quotIt was very <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nicole_Scherzinger" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nicole_Scherzinger" target="_blank">cold</a> in a sense before The <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Caf%C3%A9" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Caf%C3%A9" target="_blank">cafe</a> is very good in that it doesn't move you on urgently you can stay there all day just drinking <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Coffee" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Coffee" target="_blank">coffee</a> And the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Free_will" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Free_will" target="_blank">free</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wi-Fi" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wi-Fi" target="_blank">wifi</a> has been really helpful&quot says <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Francis_of_Assisi" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Francis_of_Assisi" target="_blank">Francis</a>&quotIt is all these tiny things that are saying <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hanging" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hanging" target="_blank">hang</a> around you can just be here all the time and that made it a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" target="_blank">place</a> where <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> felt comfortable and that is a good <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" target="_blank">place</a> to breed <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" target="_blank">art</a>&quot <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" target="_blank">Artists</a> like to work in a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" target="_blank">place</a> like that And then the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public" target="_blank">public</a> like to come and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hanging" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hanging" target="_blank">hang</a> out in a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portland_Place" target="_blank">place</a> where <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" target="_blank">artists</a> are <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hanging" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hanging" target="_blank">hanging</a> out&quotIt was getting back to some of that early <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Spirituality" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Spirituality" target="_blank">spirit</a> of the Third Eye&quotOriginally from <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Northern_Ireland" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Northern_Ireland" target="_blank">Northern Ireland</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Francis_of_Assisi" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Francis_of_Assisi" target="_blank">Francis</a> studied and worked at the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/University_of_Glasgow" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/University_of_Glasgow" target="_blank">University of Glasgow</a> before moving to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow_School_of_Art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Glasgow_School_of_Art" target="_blank">Glasgow School of Art</a> where he still <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Teacher" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Teacher" target="_blank">teaches</a> and does research and then the CCAAs well as organising the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Archive" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Archive" target="_blank">archiving</a> of 40 <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Millennium" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Millennium" target="_blank">years</a>' of material stretching back to the earliest days of the Third Eye Centre his <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Character_%28arts%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Character_%28arts%29" target="_blank">role</a> is very much looking to the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Human_League" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Human_League" target="_blank">future</a>&quotI think there was a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Reason" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Reason" target="_blank">reasonable</a> amount of annoyance at the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Opening_credits" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Opening_credits" target="_blank">opening</a> It didn't have an <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Opening_ceremony" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Opening_ceremony" target="_blank">opening ceremony</a>&quot he says&quotI think a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" target="_blank">lot</a> of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> loved the Third Eye deeply and when it shut and this other place just opened they weren't pleased with that The <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> had a very different sense of what it was there for and it seemed to be there for <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" target="_blank">contemporary art</a>&quotIt was very much more about uniting to the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" target="_blank">contemporary art</a> world in Europe and the rest of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Great_Britain" target="_blank">Britain</a> and that seemed to imply that would be great if you liked <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" target="_blank">contemporary art</a> but if you liked the puppet shows that used to happen before and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Wanted" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Wanted" target="_blank">wanted</a> to come into the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Caf%C3%A9" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Caf%C3%A9" target="_blank">cafe</a> for a roll those things were no longer there&quotSo there was a sense of it tightening its focus onto <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Contemporary_art" target="_blank">contemporary art</a> and that alienated a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" target="_blank">lot</a> of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> who probably liked the more <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Community" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Community" target="_blank">community</a> atmosphere and the openness of the Third Eye&quotI think that has gone full circle&quotA total of 80% of activity in the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> now is by other people underwriting <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Artist" target="_blank">artist</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public_housing" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Public_housing" target="_blank">projects</a> that otherwise might not see the light of dayAnd four <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/City" target="_blank">cities</a> in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second_Boer_War" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second_Boer_War" target="_blank">South Africa</a> including <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Johannesburg" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Johannesburg" target="_blank">Johannesburg</a> and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cape_Town" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cape_Town" target="_blank">Cape Town</a> are keen to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Richie_Havens" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Richie_Havens" target="_blank">follow</a> the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/California_College_of_the_Arts" target="_blank">CCA</a> example&quotThere have been a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" target="_blank">lot</a> of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Debate" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Debate" target="_blank">discussions</a> around sharing the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Open_source" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Open_source" target="_blank">open source</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Model_%28art%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Model_%28art%29" target="_blank">model</a> When there's not a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" target="_blank">lot</a> of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Money" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Money" target="_blank">money</a> to spend on <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Art" target="_blank">art</a> they could actually do a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" target="_blank">lot</a> more&quot he comments&quotAnd a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Land_lot" target="_blank">lot</a> of <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> want to be involved in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second_Boer_War" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Second_Boer_War" target="_blank">South Africa</a> The <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Country_music" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Country_music" target="_blank">country</a> is <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Amazing_Grace" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Amazing_Grace" target="_blank">amazing</a> for <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Culture" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Culture" target="_blank">culture</a> but the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Percy_Bysshe_Shelley" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Percy_Bysshe_Shelley" target="_blank">question</a> is how do you find places and an <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Economy" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Economy" target="_blank">economic</a> way to work that&quot
